EDA of Titanic Data

David West

8/13/2020

1 Intro

This is an EDA of the Titanic data set on Kaggle. The objective is to understand the data set and eventually create a predictive model for survival rate.

1.1 Data Dictionary

The following descriptions were provided on Kaggle.

dictionary
## # A tibble: 10 x 3
##    Variable Definition                        Key                               
##    <chr>    <chr>                             <chr>                             
##  1 survival Survival                          "0 = No, 1 = Yes"                 
##  2 pclass   Ticket class                      "1 = 1st, 2 = 2nd, 3 = 3rd"       
##  3 sex      Sex                               ""                                
##  4 Age      Age in years                      ""                                
##  5 sibsp    # of siblings / spouses aboard t~ ""                                
##  6 parch    # of parents / children aboard t~ ""                                
##  7 ticket   Ticket number                     ""                                
##  8 fare     Passenger fare                    ""                                
##  9 cabin    Cabin number                      ""                                
## 10 embarked Port of Embarkation               "C = Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S~

The following notes were provided about the variables:
pclass: A proxy for socio-economic status (SES)
1st = Upper
2nd = Middle
3rd = Lower

age: Age is fractional if less than 1. If the age is estimated, is it in the form of xx.5

sibsp: The dataset defines family relations in this way
Sibling = brother, sister, stepbrother, stepsister
Spouse = husband, wife (mistresses and fiancs were ignored)

parch: The dataset defines family relations in this way
Parent = mother, father
Child = daughter, son, stepdaughter, stepson
Some children travelled only with a nanny, therefore parch=0 for them.

Now, lets look at each variable one at a time.

3.1 PassengerID

Im guessing this a unique identifier for each passenger. Below is a quick summary:

summary(train$PassengerId)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     1.0   223.5   446.0   446.0   668.5   891.0

No NAs. Thats good. If PassengerId is a true unique identifier, the max PassengerId number should equal the number of rows of data.

nrow(train)
## [1] 891

They are both 891. The summary from First Look shows no NAs either. This variable looks good.

3.2 Survived

According to the data dictionary, 1 means the passenger survived and 0 means the passenger did not. Below is a quick summary:

summary(train$Survived)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.0000  0.0000  0.0000  0.3838  1.0000  1.0000

Looks like the average survival rate was only 0.3838384. Not so good The data looks fine though.

Just like the James Cameron movie, survival rate is lower for lower SESs. This is definitely a good predictive variable / feature.

3.4.1 New Features

The script below will create the following new features: LastName, Title, OtherName (i.e.name in parentheses), OtherNameExists (a TRUE or FALSE of whether there is something in the OtherName column).

train2 <- train %>% 
  mutate(
    LastName = str_extract(Name, "^.*(?=,)"),
    Title = str_extract(Name, "(?<=, )[^.]*"),
    OtherName = str_extract(Name, "(?<=\\()[^\\)]*"),
    OtherNameExists = is.na(OtherName)==FALSE
  )

Below shows the first 20 rows of Names and the new features.

df <- train2 %>% 
  select(Name, LastName, Title, OtherName, OtherNameExists)

3.6.1 New Feature

Age will be broken into 20 bins. The bins will not follow the same approach as the histogram. Instead, the bins will be calculated based on cumulative density (i.e quantile 0 to 0.05 will be the first bin, 0.05 to 0.10 will be the next bin, and so on). This new feature will be called AgeBin

train3 <- train2 %>% 
  mutate(
    AgeBin = case_when(
      is.na(Age) ~ NA_integer_,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.05, na.rm = T) ~  1L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.10, na.rm = T) ~  2L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.15, na.rm = T) ~  3L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.20, na.rm = T) ~  4L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.25, na.rm = T) ~  5L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.30, na.rm = T) ~  6L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.35, na.rm = T) ~  7L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.40, na.rm = T) ~  8L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.45, na.rm = T) ~  9L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.50, na.rm = T) ~ 10L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.55, na.rm = T) ~ 11L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.60, na.rm = T) ~ 12L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.65, na.rm = T) ~ 13L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.70, na.rm = T) ~ 14L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.75, na.rm = T) ~ 15L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.80, na.rm = T) ~ 16L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.85, na.rm = T) ~ 17L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.90, na.rm = T) ~ 18L,
      Age < quantile(train2$Age,0.95, na.rm = T) ~ 19L,
      TRUE ~ 20L))

parch: The dataset defines family relations in this way
Parent = mother, father
Child = daughter, son, stepdaughter, stepson

3.9.1 New Features

Looks like some ticket numbers have pre-fixes. This can create two new features: TicketPrefix, TicketNo.

train4 <- train3 %>% 
  mutate(
    TicketPrefix = str_extract(Ticket, "^.*(?= \\d{3})"),
    TicketPrefix = str_remove_all(TicketPrefix, "\\."),
    TicketNo = case_when(
      str_detect(Ticket, " ") ~ str_extract(Ticket, "\\d*$"),
      TRUE ~ Ticket
    )
  )

Looks like as Fare increases, so does survival rate. However, there is an exception for Males. It appears that a Far above $200 for males results in a low survival rate. Lets try a different visual. The graphic below shows a histogram of survival (1) and death (0) by Fare at 10 bins.

df <- train4 %>% 
  mutate(Pclass = as.factor(Pclass),
         Survived = as.factor(Survived),
         Sex = as.factor(Sex))

  geom_histogram(bins = 10)

Looks like survival increase as Fare increases, but its harder to visualize with the higher fares as the sample size decreases. To overcome this, the y axis can be converted to a percent breakout instead of a count. See below:

ggplot(df, aes(x=Fare, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_histogram(position="fill", bins = 10)
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (geom_bar).

Thats much easier to visualize. It appears that survival rate increase as Fare goes up and then decreases after a 200+ Fare. Also, the data past 400 might be an outlier. Lets remove any Fare past the 99% CI and see what this graphic looks like then.

df <- train4 %>% 
  mutate(Pclass = as.factor(Pclass),
         Survived = as.factor(Survived),
         Sex = as.factor(Sex)) %>% 
  filter(Fare < quantile(Fare, .99))

ggplot(df, aes(x=Fare, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_histogram(position="fill", bins = 10)
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_bar).

Looks like the highest change of survival is if some one but a ticket in between 100 and 200. Now lets look at this same graphic but broken up by Pclass and Sex.

ggplot(df, aes(x=Fare, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_histogram(position="fill", bins = 10) +
  facet_grid(Pclass~Sex)
## Warning: Removed 56 rows containing missing values (geom_bar).

Interesting, female passengers in Pclass 3 have a lower survival rate if they had a more expensive ticket. Also, male passengers that had a ticket fare past 200 had a survival rate of zero. ### New Feature Lets try this analysis one more time, with a different approach. Fare will be broken into 20 bins. The bins will not follow the same approach as the histogram. Instead, the bins will be calculated based on cumulative density (i.e quantile 0 to 0.05 will be the first bin, 0.05 to 0.10 will be the next bin, and so on). This new feature will be called FareBin

train5 <- train4 %>% 
  mutate(
    FareBin = case_when(
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.05) ~  1L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.10) ~  2L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.15) ~  3L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.20) ~  4L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.25) ~  5L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.30) ~  6L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.35) ~  7L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.40) ~  8L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.45) ~  9L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.50) ~ 10L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.55) ~ 11L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.60) ~ 12L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.65) ~ 13L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.70) ~ 14L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.75) ~ 15L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.80) ~ 16L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.85) ~ 17L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.90) ~ 18L,
      Fare < quantile(train4$Fare,0.95) ~ 19L,
      TRUE ~ 20L))

Lets look at the survival rate for each FareBin.

df <- train5 %>% 
  group_by(FareBin) %>% 
  summarise(
    SurvivalRate = mean(Survived),
    n = n()
  ) %>% 
  ungroup()

Pclass and Sex appear to be the strongest predictive variables. This will be confirmed during the model building EDA. There may be more feature engineering to come but I think this is a good start.
